     Now assume  ${\text{rad}}\left( {C_R ^\lambda  } \right) = C_R ^\lambda  {\text{ in }}A$, so $\left\langle {x,y} \right\rangle  = 0$ for any $x \in C_R ^\lambda  ,y \in \,_L C^\lambda  $.  To show ${\text{rad}}\left( {C^\lambda  } \right) = C^\lambda  {\text{ in }}A_i $ it suffices to show that  $\left\langle {C_t^\lambda  ,{}_sC^\lambda  } \right\rangle _i  = 0$ for any $t,s$.  Take any $D \in D\left( {M,i,r} \right)$ and choose $C \in C\left( {i,r} \right)$ such that $\rho  = \psi _D  \circ \phi _C $ is bijective.  Then apply lemma \ref{ll3.2}(b) with $\pi  = \rho ^{ - 1} $ to get  $\left\langle {C_t ^\lambda  ,\,_s C^\lambda  } \right\rangle _i  = \left\langle {C_t ^\lambda  ,\rho \pi  \cdot \,_s C^\lambda  } \right\rangle _i  = \left\langle {C_{\left( {D,t} \right)} ^\lambda  ,\,\pi ' \cdot \,_{\left( {C,s} \right)} C^\lambda  } \right\rangle  = 0$.
